The article is a Presidential Memoranda issued on April 6, 2018, with the subject of ending "Catch and Release" at the border of the United States and directing other enhancements to immigration enforcement. The memorandum highlights the threats to national security and public safety posed by human smuggling operations, drug smuggling, entry of gang members and criminals at the border, as well as the backlog of immigration-related cases and personnel shortages in border security and immigration enforcement. The memorandum directs the Secretary of Homeland Security, in coordination with other departments, to submit a report detailing measures to end "catch and release" practices within 45 days. It also directs the Attorney General and Secretary of Homeland Security to submit a report identifying additional resources or authorities needed to end "catch and release" practices within 75 days. Additionally, the memorandum instructs the Secretary of State and Secretary of Homeland Security to submit a report within 60 days detailing measures, including diplomatic measures, against countries that refuse to accept the repatriation of their nationals. The memorandum concludes with general provisions, stating that it should be implemented consistent with applicable law and subject to the availability of appropriations, and that it does not create any enforceable rights or benefits.